</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Two words: Activation Energy.  <br>
<br>
Many chemical reactions have what is called a potential energy barrier.  This means in order for the chemical reaction to proceed, the reactants need to have a certain energy or be at a certain temperature.  The standard reaction where hydrogen and oxygen to produce water:<br>
<br>
2H2 + O2 === 2H2O<br>
<br>
Requires higher temperatures than room temperature.  I do not have a CRC handbook on hand, so I cannot give you the exact temperature.  I can assure you it is above the boiling point of water.<br>
<br>
Some of the hydrogen molecules will be able to react with the oxygen at room temperature since temperature is a mean distribution of molecular velocities.  However, these are on the tail of the distribution and most will likely rise quickly to the upper atmosphere being far lighter than air and all.<br>
<br>
